h her brother Thoby, and what Ginsberg meant when referring to the mouth feel of Shakespeare’s verse. From Hughes’s attempts to find a “skeleton key” to all of Shakespeare’s plays to Berryman’s tormented efforts to edit King Lear, Leinwand reveals the palpable energy and conviction with which these seven writers engaged with Shakespeare, their moments of utter self-confidence and profound vexation. In uncovering these intense public and private reactions, The Great William connects major writers’ hitherto unremarked scenes of reading Shakespeare with our own.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / General.2bisacsh  ashakespeare, the bard, poet, famous person, playwright, author, close reading, reader, english major, humanities, college, university, academic, scholarly, research, educational, samuel taylor coleridge, virginia woolfe, charles olson, john berryman, allen ginsberg, ted hughes, intellectual, analysis, critique, critical, theory, theoretical, marginalia, letters, journals, primary source.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2016z978311071098440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226367699423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226367699/original  a978-3-11-071098-4  University of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2016b2016  aGBV-deGruyter-alles